%%TITLE
Prevalence of pneumococcal disease, serotype distribution, and antimicrobial susceptibility in Mexican children younger than 5 years of age.
%%ABSTRACT
Background and Aims. Streptococcus pneumoniae constitutes one of the main causes of sepsis, bacteremia and meningitis (pneumococcal invasive disease e PID), and pneumonia in infants and small children. Antipneumococcal vaccination in Mexico is expected to be a useful strategy to reduce morbimortality due to this cause. We undertook this study to determine the prevalence of PID and pneumonia and the PCV vaccination status of affected children as well as serotype distribution and antimicrobial susceptibility of pneumococcal strains responsible for PID in infants and small children in Mexico.
Methods. From March 2010eJune 2011, a prospective multicenter study was carried out in four states in Mexico to determine the prevalence of bacteremia, meningitis, septic arthritis and pneumonia due to S. pneumoniae and other microorganisms in children from 28 dayse59 months of age. Isolated pneumococcal strains were serotyped and their antimicrobial resistance determined.
Results. During the study period, 545 children were diagnosed with bacteremia, meningitis, septic arthritis or pneumonia; 46.7% of these clinical entities occurred among children !12 months of age. Community-acquired pneumonia was the most prevalent disease. It was possible to identify a causal microorganism in 55 cases, from which 80% were S. pneumoniae. Fifteen percent of patients with PID died. The most prevalent pneumococcal serotypes were 19A, 35B, 19F and 6A. 10.2% of nonmeningeal strains were resistant to meropenem and 82% were resistant to TMP/SMX.
%%MATERIALS AND METHODS
Study Design and Population
From March 2010eJune 2011 we conducted a prospective multicenter study to determine the prevalence of bacter- emia, meningitis, septic arthritis and pneumonia caused by S. pneumoniae and other bacteria in children from 28 dayse59 months of age who sought medical attention at eight sentinel hospitals distributed in four states as follows: three states located in the northern part of the country, three from the central region, and two from the southeast region of Mexico. Two of these hospitals belong to the IMSS, and the rest belong to the MH. Eligible children included those with signs and symptoms suggestive of bacteremia, menin- gitis, septic arthritis or community-acquired pneumonia (CAP) according to Good Clinical Practices and WHO criteria . Once the inclusion criteria were verified, informed consent was obtained from the childâ€™s parent(s) or guardian(s). For every patient, perinatal background, immunization history (through verification of National Health Card or nominal census at the health care facility), clinical, radiological, laboratory and sociodemographic information were recorded in the corresponding case report form. During hospitalization, evolution of every case was followed through clinical assessment and clinical file review.
Study Definitions
A diagnosis of PID was considered when a pneumococcal strain was isolated in a patient with diagnosis of bacter- emia, meningitis, septic arthritis, and those pneumonias in which a pneumococcal strain was isolated from blood. Bacterial meningitis was considered in those children with clinical features suggestive of meningitis such as fever and history of one of the following signs: neck stiffness, altered consciousness with no other alternative central nervous system diagnosis or other meningeal sign, and cerebro- spinal fluid (CSF) with at least one of the following charac- teristics: turbid appearance, leukocytosis (O100 cells/ mm3), or leukocytosis (10e100 cells/ mm3) with either
an elevated protein (O100 mg/dL) or decreased glucose (!40 mg/dL). Pneumococcal meningitis was considered when clinical features and abnormalities on CSF were accompanied by positive CSF and/or blood cultures and/ or identification of S. pneumoniae by antigen detection methods (latex agglutination) or gram stain in CSF . A diagnosis of pneumococcal pneumonia (PP) was considered when a pneumococcal strain was isolated from bronchial aspirate (BA) in patients with CAP. All pneumonia cases with empyema, pleural effusion or multiple foci were classified as complicated pneumonias (CP). Diagnosis of bacteremia was considered in those patients with fever $38.0 C with !7 days of duration, without clinical evidence of an infectious process, leukocy- tosis O15,000/mm3, pulse oximetry $95%, unaltered thoracic X-ray, and isolation of a pathogenic microor- ganism in a blood culture . Patients without isola- tion of a pathogenic microorganism were classified as suspected bacteremia.
Clinical Samples and Laboratory Methods
A minimum of one blood sample for culture was taken from each patient with suspicion of bacteremia, meningitis, septic arthritis or CAP. Whenever possible, a second sample was ob- tained 30 min after the first one. According to clinical criteria, CSF, pleural fluid (PF), synovial fluid (SF) and BA, among others, were obtained for culture. Culture bottles (Pediatric- Plus hemoculture bottles (Becton Dickinson, BD, Franklin Lakes, NJ) or BacT/Alert PF (Pediatric) hemoculture bottles (BioM erieux, Durham, NC) were used, and initial identifica- tion of bacterial isolates was done using BacT/ALERT (Bio- M erieux) or BACTEC (Becton Dickinson, BD) automated equipment. BA samples obtained by Muller traps were as- sessed for quality according to Pezzlo and Murray ; these samples were directly inoculated into blood and choc- olate agar plates. Capsular serotype was determined using the Quellung reaction with sera from the Statens Serum Institute (Copenhagen, Denmark). Antimicrobial suscepti- bility was determined by broth microdilution according to the Clinical and Laboratory Standards Institute (CLSI) guide- lines . LA was performed on all CSF samples for detection of polysaccharide antigens of Neisseria meningiti- dis A,B; Escherichia coli K1, C, Y/W135; Haemophilus influenza type b; S. pneumoniae, and group B Streptococcus (Pastorex Meningitis, Bio-Rad Laboratories) .
Prevalence and Risk Estimations
Prevalence was obtained by estimating the frequency of patients from 28 dayse59 months of age who were admitted at sentinel hospitals and who met the definitive clinical criteria of bacteremia, meningitis, septic arthritis and CAP in relation to the total number of patients with a presumptive diagnosis of the previously mentioned clin- ical entities. We performed a bivariate analysis to identify risk of becoming ill due to serotypes included in PCV7, risk of death due to IPD among vaccinated children, and risk for developing a CP among cases caused by 19A serotype. Data were analyzed with EPI-INFO 7 3.5.3. 2008.
The study was approved by the Human Biomedical Research Institutional Committee at Salvador Zubiran National Institute of Medical Science and Nutrition, National Institute of Public Health, and the Research Coor- dination at IMSS.
